# =============================================================================
# METHOD SECTION (Plain Language)
# =============================================================================
print("\n" + "=" * 80)
print("METHOD")
print("=" * 80)
print(f"""
How This Analysis Was Done (Plain Language)
-------------------------------------------

This study estimates the economic value that Pennsylvania's public colleges and
universities bring to the state. Here is a step-by-step description of how the
analysis was carried out.

1. GATHERING THE DATA
   We collected publicly available data on every public higher education
   institution in Pennsylvania, including the four state-related universities
   (Penn State, Pitt, Temple, and Lincoln), the 10 PASSHE universities, and
   the 15 community colleges. The data include how many students attend, how
   many people each school employs, how much they spend, and how much research
   funding they receive. All figures come from official institutional reports,
   the PASSHE system, federal databases, and the SHEEO State Higher Education
   Finance report for fiscal year 2024.

2. MEASURING ECONOMIC RIPPLE EFFECTS
   When a university hires staff or buys supplies, that money flows through
   the local economy. Employees spend their wages at local businesses, which
   in turn hire more workers, and so on. To capture these ripple effects, we
   used the Bureau of Economic Analysis RIMS II multipliers, which are the
   federal government's standard tool for estimating how each dollar of
   spending in one industry creates additional dollars of activity across the
   broader economy. We applied the multiplier specific to the education sector
   in Pennsylvania (approximately 1.91).

3. ESTIMATING EMPLOYMENT IMPACT
   We counted direct jobs (people employed by the institutions) and then used
   the RIMS II employment multiplier to estimate additional jobs created in
   the wider economy (suppliers, local retailers, service providers, etc.).
   We also accounted for student spending, which supports local businesses
   near each campus.

4. CALCULATING TAX REVENUE
   We estimated the state and local tax revenue generated by all the economic
   activity tied to higher education. This includes income taxes paid by
   employees, sales taxes from spending, and property taxes from university-
   related real estate. We used effective tax rates from Pennsylvania's
   Department of Revenue and the Census Bureau.

5. COMPUTING RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI)
   We compared the total economic impact and tax revenue generated against
   the amount Pennsylvania taxpayers invest through state appropriations.
   This gives a simple ratio: for every dollar the state puts in, how many
   dollars of economic activity or tax revenue come back.

6. TRACKING HISTORICAL TRENDS
   We compiled 15 years of historical data (2009-2023) on enrollment, state
   funding, and tuition levels. We adjusted all dollar figures for inflation
   so comparisons over time are fair. We also adjusted for wage growth, which
   shows how state funding has kept pace (or not) with the rising cost of
   employing faculty and staff.

7. ANALYZING BRAIN DRAIN
   We looked at what share of Pennsylvania college graduates leave the state
   after finishing their degrees, using Census Bureau migration data and the
   Joint Economic Committee's 2019 Brain Drain report. We estimated the
   resulting lost tax revenue and economic productivity.

8. COUNTY-LEVEL BREAKDOWN
   We mapped each institution to its county and distributed economic impacts
   geographically, so policymakers can see how higher education contributes
   to local economies across the state, not just in major metro areas.

9. FREE-COLLEGE SIMULATION
   We modeled what would happen if Pennsylvania covered tuition and fees for
   all in-state students at public institutions. We estimated the cost to
   the state (accounting for existing financial aid that would be redirected),
   projected how many additional students would enroll and graduate (using
   data from Tennessee's Promise program as a benchmark), and then calculated
   the long-term economic returns over 5, 10, 20, and 40 years. This
   simulation tracks additional tax revenue from higher earnings, GDP growth
   from a more educated workforce, and reductions in brain drain.

10. MONTE CARLO UNCERTAINTY ANALYSIS
    Because no economic estimate is perfectly precise, we ran the entire model
    10,000 times, each time randomly varying key inputs within plausible
    ranges (for example, letting the economic multiplier range between 1.7
    and 2.1 instead of using a single fixed value). This produces a range of
    outcomes rather than a single point estimate, showing the 5th percentile
    (conservative), median (middle), and 95th percentile (optimistic) results.
    We also ran a version where the random inputs are correlated with each
    other (since in a recession, for instance, multipliers and enrollment
    and state funding all tend to move together), which gives a more
    realistic picture of worst-case and best-case scenarios.

11. ADDRESSING KNOWN LIMITATIONS
    We added four additional analyses to address the most common critiques
    of economic impact studies like this one:
    a) Dynamic feedback effects: We modeled how more graduates might change
       wage levels over time, which feeds back into enrollment decisions.
    b) Crowding-out: We estimated how much of the free-college spending
       would displace other state programs, and whether the net effect is
       still positive.
    c) Private institutions: We estimated the economic contribution of
       Pennsylvania's private colleges and universities to give a complete
       picture of higher education's total footprint.
    d) Correlated Monte Carlo: Instead of treating each uncertain input
       independently, we modeled how economic variables move together
       during booms and recessions.
""")
# =============================================================================
# ASSUMPTIONS SECTION (Plain Language)
# =============================================================================
print("\n" + "=" * 80)
print("ASSUMPTIONS")
print("=" * 80)
print(f"""
Key Assumptions and What They Mean (Plain Language)
----------------------------------------------------

Every economic analysis rests on a set of assumptions. Below we list each major
assumption, explain it in everyday terms, and note where it might over- or
under-state the results.

A. ECONOMIC MULTIPLIER VALUES
   Assumption: Every dollar a university spends generates roughly $1.91 in
   total economic activity across the state.
   What this means: If a school pays a professor $100,000, that salary doesn't
   just benefit the professor. She spends money at local stores, pays rent,
   hires a plumber, and so on. The multiplier captures that chain reaction.
   We used the official federal RIMS II multiplier for the education sector in
   Pennsylvania. In our uncertainty analysis, we let this value range from
   1.7 to 2.1 to account for the possibility that the true ripple effect is
   somewhat smaller or larger.

B. ENROLLMENT RESPONSE TO FREE TUITION
   Assumption: Making college free would increase enrollment by about 10% in
   Year 1, growing to roughly 20% over several years.
   What this means: We assume that some people who currently cannot afford
   college (or who choose not to take on debt) would enroll if tuition were
   free. The 10% starting figure is based on what actually happened in
   Tennessee when it launched a similar program. This is a moderate estimate;
   some studies suggest the effect could be larger, while others find smaller
   gains.

C. GRADUATION RATES
   Assumption: Among the additional students who enroll because of free
   tuition, about 5% more will complete their degree compared to the current
   graduation rate.
   What this means: Free tuition removes a major financial barrier, which
   reduces the number of students who drop out for money-related reasons.
   The 5-percentage-point boost is conservative; Tennessee saw somewhat
   larger improvements.

D. LIFETIME EARNINGS PREMIUM
   Assumption: A bachelor's degree holder earns about $1.2 million more over
   a lifetime than someone with only a high school diploma. An associate's
   degree adds roughly $400,000.
   What this means: College graduates tend to earn more, pay more in taxes,
   and rely less on public assistance. These figures come from Georgetown
   University's Center on Education and the Workforce. They represent
   averages and will vary by field of study, but they are widely used
   benchmarks in policy analysis.

E. BRAIN DRAIN RATE
   Assumption: About 30% of Pennsylvania college graduates leave the state
   after graduation. Free college could reduce this to about 23%.
   What this means: When graduates leave, PA loses the economic benefit of
   having educated them. We assume that students who attend for free feel a
   stronger connection to the state and are somewhat more likely to stay.
   The 7-percentage-point reduction is an estimate; the actual change would
   depend on job availability, personal preferences, and other factors.

F. EXISTING FINANCIAL AID OFFSET
   Assumption: About 45% of the gross cost of free tuition would be offset
   by existing federal and state financial aid that already covers part of
   students' tuition.
   What this means: The sticker price of free college is not the true cost
   to the state, because Pell Grants, PA State Grants, and institutional aid
   already pay a significant share of tuition for many students. We estimated
   this offset using actual aid data. If the offset turns out to be smaller,
   the net cost to the state would be higher.

G. DISCOUNT RATE FOR FUTURE BENEFITS
   Assumption: We use a 3% annual discount rate when comparing future
   economic benefits to present-day costs.
   What this means: A dollar earned 20 years from now is worth less than a
   dollar today (because of inflation and opportunity cost). The 3% rate is
   a standard choice for public policy analysis. Using a higher rate would
   make the long-term benefits appear smaller; a lower rate would make them
   appear larger.

H. STATIC VS. DYNAMIC ECONOMY
   Assumption: The baseline model treats the economy as a snapshot, not a
   moving picture. Prices, wages, and enrollment don't adjust in response
   to the policy change.
   What this means: In reality, flooding the labor market with more
   graduates could slightly lower the wage premium for a degree, which
   might discourage some future students. Our Phase 8 analysis partially
   addresses this by modeling wage feedback effects, but the core model
   does not.

I. CROWDING-OUT OF OTHER STATE SPENDING
   Assumption: In the baseline model, we assume no displacement of other
   state programs. In Phase 8, we test what happens if 25-75% of free-
   college spending comes at the expense of other programs.
   What this means: If the state pays for free college, that money has to
   come from somewhere (higher taxes, budget cuts elsewhere, or new revenue).
   The baseline optimistically assumes new money; the Phase 8 sensitivity
   analysis shows results under more realistic budget-tradeoff scenarios.

J. PRIVATE INSTITUTIONS
   Assumption: The baseline model only covers public institutions. Phase 8
   adds estimates for private colleges based on IPEDS data.
   What this means: Pennsylvania has a large private higher education sector
   (over 100 institutions). By initially focusing only on public schools, the
   baseline understates the total economic role of higher education in the
   state. The Phase 8 addition corrects this.

K. MULTIPLIER INDEPENDENCE VS. CORRELATION
   Assumption: In the basic Monte Carlo simulation, each uncertain input
   varies independently. In the correlated version, inputs move together.
   What this means: In the real world, when the economy is weak, state
   funding falls AND enrollment changes AND spending power drops, all at
   once. The basic version understates how bad a bad scenario can get (and
   how good a good scenario can get). The correlated version provides a
   more realistic range.

L. HOSPITAL ECONOMIC ACTIVITY
   Assumption: University-affiliated hospitals (Penn State Hershey, Temple
   University Hospital, UPMC/Pitt) are included as part of higher education's
   economic footprint.
   What this means: These hospitals employ thousands of people and generate
   billions in economic activity, but they also serve a healthcare mission
   that is partially independent of the educational mission. Including them
   gives a larger but arguably fair picture, since these hospitals exist
   because of their university affiliations.

M. DATA VINTAGE
   Assumption: Most data are from 2022-2024 academic and fiscal years.
   What this means: The analysis reflects recent conditions but not
   real-time changes. If enrollment has shifted significantly since the
   most recent data release, some estimates may be slightly outdated.
""")

